{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569092"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:25:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:25:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21937"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21937"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.15,0.59,0.11,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14857"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111545"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14857"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21937"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93634"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"147"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9673"},{"type":"tags","id":"11505"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"38311"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38312"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38313"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38314"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38315"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38316"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39671"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43754"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111545"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with increasing shortness of breath with associated chest tightness in the mornings, occurring most days of the week over the past four weeks. He reports night-time symptoms approximately once a week, which responds to his inhaler. He has a 20-year medical history of asthma. His only medication is regular low dose budesonide-formoterol as needed, which he has been using an average of two puffs twice per day. He denies any fever, cough, weight loss, or anorexia. He is a non-smoker. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His chest is clear on auscultation with no evidence of infection. His inhaler technique is correct on demonstration.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fluticasone-vilanterol-umeclidinium inhaler daily","Fluticasone 100 mcg MDI daily","Budesonide-formoterol DPI as maintenance-and-reliever therapy","Ipratropium bromide MDI four times daily as required","Prednisolone 40 mg PO once daily for five days"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with multiple indicators of poorly controlled asthma: daytime symptoms most days of the week, frequent use of low dose budesonide-formoterol medication, and night-time symptoms. Another indicator of asthma control not present in this case is limitation of activities. According to the Australian Asthma Handbook, these features indicate poor asthma control requiring a step-up in therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022https://files.nationalasthma.org.au/resources/NAC040-Selecting-and-Adjusting-Asthma-Medication-Chart-2024_A4_LR.pdf\u0022\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelecting and adjusting asthma medications for adults and adolescents:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/a\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs-needed SABA alone\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBudesonide\u2013formoterol (low dose as needed) OR Regular daily maintenance ICS (low dose) + SABA reliever as needed\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EREGULAR DAILY ICS\u2013LABA (\u003Cstrong\u003ELOW\u003C/strong\u003E DOSE): ICS\u2013formoterol maintenance-and-reliever therapy (low dose as regular daily maintenance plus low dose as needed) OR Regular daily maintenance ICS\u2013LABA combination (low dose) + SABA reliever as needed\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EREGULAR DAILY ICS\u2013LABA (\u003Cstrong\u003EMEDIUM\u2013HIGH\u003C/strong\u003E DOSE): ICS\u2013formoterol maintenance-and-reliever therapy (medium dose as regular daily maintenance plus low dose as needed) OR Regular daily maintenance ICS\u2013LABA combination (medium\u2013high dose) + SABA reliever as needed\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdd-on specialised treatment\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBudesonide-formoterol DPI\u003C/strong\u003E as single maintenance-and-reliever therapy (SMART) is the most appropriate option for this patient. This approach provides both an inhaled corticosteroid (ICS) to treat underlying inflammation and a long-acting beta-agonist (LABA) for bronchodilation. The SMART approach allows the patient to use the same inhaler for both regular maintenance dosing and as-needed relief, which simplifies the regimen and ensures that additional reliever doses are accompanied by anti-inflammatory medication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluticasone MDI\u003C/strong\u003E daily would provide anti-inflammatory effects but would be insufficient given the multiple indicators of poor control. While an ICS alone might be considered for mild persistent asthma, this patient\u0027s symptoms suggest he would benefit from the additional bronchodilation provided by a LABA component.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluticasone-vilanterol-umeclidinium inhaler\u003C/strong\u003E is a triple therapy combination containing an ICS, LABA, and long-acting muscarinic antagonist (LAMA). Triple therapy is typically reserved for patients with severe asthma who remain uncontrolled despite optimised ICS-LABA therapy. This patient has not yet been trialled on appropriate ICS-LABA maintenance therapy, making triple therapy premature at this stage. Triple therapy is prescribed as a regular medicine, and cannot be used as a PRN medicine due to adverse effects with excessive muscarinic antagonism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIpratropium bromide MDI\u003C/strong\u003E is a short-acting muscarinic antagonist primarily used for chronic obstructive pulmonary disease or as an add-on therapy in acute asthma exacerbations. It is not recommended as a regular controller medication for asthma and would not address the underlying inflammation. Regular use of ipratropium for asthma maintenance is not supported by current guidelines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E PO is reserved for acute exacerbations with significant symptoms affecting daily activities or quality of life. While this patient has poor control, he does not appear to be experiencing an acute exacerbation requiring oral corticosteroids. The focus should be on establishing appropriate long-term controller therapy rather than short-term symptom relief.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Maintenance-and-reliever therapy with budesonide-formoterol is an effective option for patients with poorly controlled asthma.","Frequent use of short-acting beta-agonists (\u003E2 days/week) indicates poor asthma control requiring preventer therapy.","Triple therapy (ICS-LABA-LAMA) is reserved for patients with severe asthma not controlled on ICS-LABA combinations and is not used PRN."],"references":["National Asthma Council Australia [Internet]. Melbourne: National Asthma Council Australia; 2022. Australian Asthma Handbook, Version 2.2. [Accessed June 2025]. Available at: https://www.asthmahandbook.org.au/","Reddel, H. Updated Australian guidelines for mild asthma: what\u2019s changed and why? Australian Prescriber. Updated December 1, 2020. Accessed March 24, 2024. Available from: https://australianprescriber.tg.org.au/articles/updated-australian-guidelines-for-mild-asthma-whats-changed-and-why.html","eTG complete [Internet]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2020 Mar. Maintenance management of asthma in adults and adolescents: [2015 Mar] Available from:\u00a0https://www.tg.org.au","Asthma Australia. Triple therapy preventers [Internet]. Melbourne: Asthma Australia; 2024 Nov 13 [cited 2025 Aug 16]. Available from: https://asthma.org.au/medicines/triple-therapy/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93634"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21937"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93634","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93634"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-16T16:35:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-17T09:38:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14857"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111545"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"upda